SIMPLE: squeak
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Squeak
<hw>Squeak</hw> <pr>(skw⟦emac⟧k)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Squeaked</conjf>
<pr>(skw⟦emac⟧kt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Squeaking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Probably of imitative origin;
cf. Sw. <ets>sqv⟦aum⟧ka</ets> to croak, Icel. <ets>skvakka</ets> to give
a sound as of water shaken in a bottle.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To utter
a sharp, shrill cry, usually of short duration; to cry with an acute
tone, as an animal; or, to make a sharp, disagreeable noise, as a pipe
or quill, a wagon wheel, a door; to creak.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who can endure to hear one of the rough old Romans
<qex>squeaking</qex> through the mouth of an eunuch?</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Zoilus calls the companions of Ulysses the
⟦ldquo⟧<qex>squeaking</qex> pigs⟦rdquo⟧ of Homer.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To break silence or secrecy for fear of pain or
punishment; to speak; to confess.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> squeal.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If he be obstinate, put a civil question to him upon the rack, and
he <qex>squeaks</qex>, I warrant him.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Squeak</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Squeak
<hw>Squeak</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A sharp, shrill, disagreeable sound
suddenly uttered, either of the human voice or of any animal or
instrument, such as is made by carriage wheels when dry, by the soles of
leather shoes, or by a pipe or reed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Squeaker</ent>⟦br⟧
